******
[2] Origin unresolved
Date: Wed 1 May 2013
Source: New Scientist [edited]
http://www.newscientist.com/article/dn23473-where-has-h7n9-bird-flu-come-from.html


The new H7N9 bird flu strain continues to spread across China. Currently, more than 120 cases have been reported across 10 provinces, and 24 deaths. Yet no one knows where the virus started, which hampers efforts to contain it. But a promising new antiviral drug may help tackle flu in the future.

In an attempt to find the source, Chinese labs have tested 68 000 samples since early March 2013. They have been taking swabs on farms and live animal markets, both from birds and the surfaces they've been in contact with. Only 46 of those samples, scattered across central and eastern China, carried the H7N9 virus: 44 from markets selling live poultry, one from urban racing pigeons and one from a wild pigeon. "Not one farm tested positive," says Juan Lubroth, chief veterinary officer of the UN Food and Agriculture Organization in Rome, Italy.

Genetic differences between the samples suggest the virus has been spreading in animals for a few months. But which animals? The carriers found to date were too far apart to sustain an epidemic. Lubroth's team has started looking for the virus in older samples from a wider range of organisms. "We're going back to our freezers and thawing samples," he says. City pigeons are also likely to come under closer scrutiny.

Hong Kong banned live poultry markets after H5N1 bird flu struck in 2004. Some Chinese cities have now shut theirs, but Lubroth fears that too hasty a response could drive the trade underground. Like H5N1, the new strain could spread to neighbouring countries, such as Viet Nam, that do not have China's ability to monitor and contain the spread of disease. Even if doctors spot cases of H7N9, there may be little they can do. Widespread use of the antiviral drug amantadine in Chinese poultry has already allowed many drug-resistant flu strains to emerge, including H7N9. So far, one H7N9 infection has resisted the common antiviral Tamiflu.

Better drugs are in the pipeline. Several pathogens, including flu and the bacteria that spark the multi-organ failure of sepsis, kill by triggering a runaway over-activation of the immune system. Eisai, a pharmaceutical company based in Tokyo, Japan, has a drug called Eritoran that blocks the response. A large clinical trial conducted in 2011 found that Eritoran is safe in people but doesn't treat sepsis. There is hope the drug might work in flu, however. This week, Stefanie Vogel at the University of Maryland Medical Center in Baltimore and colleagues found that Eritoran saved 90 per cent of mice from an otherwise lethal flu virus when it was given 2 days after infection. It also saved 1/3rd of the mice 6 days after infection. If the drug also works in people, it could prove invaluable in a future flu pandemic.

(Journal reference: Nature, DOI: 10.1038/nature12118)

[byline: Debora MacKenzie]

